

graph TD
    A[App Startup] --> B[BlueHiveApplication.onCreate]
    B --> C[GeckoWebViewManager.initialize]
    C --> D[GeckoRuntime Created Once]
    D --> E[uBlock Origin Installed]

    F[User Selects Video] --> G[DetailsScreen]
    G --> H[MainWebViewer Created]
    H --> I[Request Fresh Session]
    I --> J[GeckoWebViewManager.getSession]
    J --> K[Create New GeckoSession]
    K --> L[Attach to GeckoView]
    L --> M[Load Streaming URL]

    N[User Exits Video] --> O[MainWebViewer.onDestroy]
    O --> P[cleanup Called]
    P --> Q[GeckoWebViewManager.cleanupSession]
    Q --> R[Session Closed & Destroyed]

    S[User Opens Trailer] --> T[TrailerNavigation]
    T --> U[Creates Its Own GeckoSession]
    U --> V[Separate from MainWebViewer]

    style D fill:#90EE90
    style K fill:#FFB6C1
    style R fill:#FFB6C1




    📋 Key Points:
    One Runtime, Many Sessions

    GeckoRuntime: Created ONCE at app startup, shared by entire app
    GeckoSessions: Created fresh for each video, completely destroyed when done

    What Happens When You Navigate:

    Select Video → New MainWebViewer activity → Fresh GeckoSession created
    Exit Video → Activity destroyed → Session completely closed (not reused)
    Select Another Video → Brand new MainWebViewer → Brand new GeckoSession
    No URL changes within same session - each video gets its own isolated session

    Trailer Section Independence:
    MainWebViewer Session (Video)     TrailerNavigation Session (YouTube)
             │                                    │
             ├── Isolated                         ├── Isolated
             ├── Own cookies                      ├── Own cookies
             └── Destroyed on exit                └── Destroyed on exit
    Session Lifecycle:
    CREATE → ATTACH → LOAD URL → USER WATCHES → DESTROY
      ↑                                            ↓
      └────────────── No Reuse ───────────────────┘
    Memory Impact:

    Before (Pooling): 3 sessions kept alive, reused, potential contamination
    Now (Fresh): 0 idle sessions, each video gets clean slate, no contamination

    Why This Works Better for Streaming Sites:

    Each video load looks like a "first visit" to anti-bot systems
    No cookies/state carried between videos
    No detection of "unusual" navigation patterns
    Clean JavaScript environment every time

    The webview doesn't "restart" with URL changes because you don't change URLs within a session - you create a new session for each video. This is why you're not seeing white screens anymore - no contaminated state!